The first alternative is that in consequence of a return to State A the child will be exposed to physical or psychological harm. The requisite level of harm is that it is ‘intolerable’ (Guide para 34; Thomson v Thomson [1994] 3 SCR 551 (Supreme Court of Canada per La Forest J)), which I take to mean “severe”. The use of the verb “expose” rather than “suffer” means that the apprehended event is not the infliction of actual harm but that the child is placed in a setting which is dangerous

 Professor Perez-Verain para 29 of her report uses the concept of danger here.
